SIMPLE: dog-eared
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: dog-eared
<hw>dog"-eared`</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Having
the corners of the leaves turned down and soiled by careless or
long-continued usage; -- said of a book; <as>as, an old book with
<ex>dog-eared</ex> pages</as>.</def> <note>Making a page
<ex>dog-eared</ex> is sometimes done deliberately to mark a location in
a book.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Statute books before unopened, not <qex>dog-eared</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Ld. Mansfield.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>worn down, shabby.</def>⟦br⟧
<syn><b>Syn. --</b> eared.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>WordNet 1.5</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Dogeate</ent>⟦br⟧
